Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcoholic beverages or nonprescription controlled substances, or any prescription medicine for which the defendant does not have a current prescription.
Defendant shall not enter into any establishment where the primary purpose is the sale of alcoholic beverages.

Defendant shall participate in any and all counseling deemed appropriate by the Division of Community Corrections.
Defendant shall consent to a reasonable request of a law enforcement officer, based on probable cause, to submit to a breath, blood, saliva, or urine test for purposes of determining the quantity of alcohol or drugs in defendant's breath, blood, saliva, or urine.
Defendant shall abide by all other terms and conditions of probation deemed appropriate by the Division of Community Corrections.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA assessment and follow through with all recommendations thereof.

Case called a 9:39 AM.  Defendant Breanna Danette Becker in court with attorney Jane Ellen Bucher.  Jenna L Gill appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Bucher informs the Court matter is revolved.  Parties stipulate to the termination of the Motion for Stay of Entry of Judgment, Stipulated Conditions for Dismissal and Order for Stay of Entry of Judgment and Dismissal in this matter.  State will amend Count 2 to 961.573(1) and Defendant changes her plea to No Contest.  Attorney Bucher files Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form with the Court.  Court questions Defendant regarding Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form.  Court questions Attorney Bucher regarding Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights form.  Court finds Defendant freely, voluntarily, and intelligently accept the Defendant's plea of No Contest, and adjudicating her Guilty.  Parties stipulate to factual basis.  State makes a statement to the Court and moves to dismiss count 1 and count 3.  Court does Order.  Attorney Bucher makes a statement to the Court.  Defendant makes a statement to the Court.  State requests Defendant to report to the Sheriff's Office, directly after this hearing, for DNA collection.  Court does Order.
